title: CNU men, W&M's Liu take golf tournament titles
text:
CNU men, W&M's Liu take golf tournament titles Compiled by Daily Press 
COLLEGES: 
Men’s golf: 
Christopher Newport won the 17-team Ted Keller Memorial at Richmond-area Hanover Country Club, shooting a 36-hole total of 29-over-par 589 to edge Franklin & Marshall by one stroke. 
It was the Captains’ first regular-season tournament title since 2011. Matt DiSalvo paced CNU with a 4-over 144, while F&M’s Brad Lankler won the medal. 
Women’s golf: 
William and Mary’s Alessandra Liu won the Pinehurst (N.C.) Challenge with a three-round, 10-under-par 206, a school and tournament record. That helped the Tribe finish sixth. 
Old Dominion’s Rachel Walker tied for third by shooting a final-round 68, though ODU, with three players, didn’t factor in the team score. 
Men’s soccer: 
Joe Iraola’s goal in the 12th minute stood up as American (9-4-1) won 1-0 at Virginia (7-3-2). 
Women’s soccer: 
Host Old Dominion (5-9, 3-2 Conference USA) beat Alabama Birmingham 2-0 on goals by Kira Laurento in the first half and Deirdre Bradley in the second. 
Swimming: 
William and Mary's Jessie Ustjanauskas and Jeremiah O'Donnell were named the Colonial Athletic Association women's and men's Swimmers of the Week, respectively, after both Tribe teams defeated Towson last weekend. 
Ustjanauskas was undefeated in four races against the Tigers, sweeping the butterfly events and swimming on two relays. 
O'Donnell also went 4-for-4 with two individual victories and two relay wins. He swam a lifetime-best 55.79 seconds in the 100-yard breaststroke. 
Women's bowling: 
Norfolk State was chosen third and Hampton fifth in the MEAC's Southern Division in a poll of coaches and SIDs. 
N.C. A&T was tabbed as the Southern favorite, while Maryland Eastern Shore was chosen as the Northern favorite. 
Site switches: 
The Big South will move its basketball, baseball and outdoor track and field championships from Coastal Carolina and the Myrtle Beach, S.C., area, conference commissioner Kyle Kallander announced. Big South bylaws stipulate that members leaving with less than two years’ notice are not eligible to host championships, and Coastal Carolina announced Aug. 31 that it will join the Sun Belt Conference as of July 1, 2016. 
The men’s and women’s basketball tournaments, which were planned to be held at the same time, will be split into a March 3-6 event for men and a March 10-13 bracket for women. The sites are up for bid.
